docs.abstract: After 17 months in office, President Trump has yet to seal many major deals on trade, security, health care, immigration or gun control.

docs.lead_paragraph: WASHINGTON — President Trump likes nothing more than presenting himself as the ultimate deal maker, the master negotiator who can translate his success in business into the worlds of politics, policy and diplomacy. “That’s what I do, is deals,” he said one day last month.

headline.main: President Trump, Deal Maker? Not So Fast
headline.print_headline: For Self-Professed Negotiator, It’s Deal or (Usually) No Deal

docs.lead_paragraph: WASHINGTON — President Trump said on Monday that he would direct the Pentagon to establish a sixth branch of the armed forces dedicated to protecting American interests in outer space, an idea that has troubled lawmakers and even some members of his administration, who have cautioned that the action could create unnecessary bureaucratic responsibilities for a military already burdened by conflicts.

headline.main: Trump Orders Establishment of Space Force as Sixth Military Branch

docs.abstract: The shop offering $190 cuff links and $46 bath towels for Metro — which has been plagued by financial problems, soul-deadening delays and electrical fires — has been called “tone-deaf.”
docs.snippet: The shop offering $190 cuff links and $46 bath towels for Metro — which has been plagued by financial problems, soul-deadening delays and electrical fires — has been called “tone-deaf.”
docs.lead_paragraph: WASHINGTON — At the top of a shuddering escalator in a dimly lit tunnel this week, a conga drummer played and cameras flashed at the grand opening of the M Shop, a pop-up hawking $190 cuff links, $45 yoga pants and $46 bath towels emblazoned with the “iconic” (the ad says) brand of Metro, Washington’s subway system.

headline.main: Washington’s Unloved Subway Opens a Swag Shop. Riders Aren’t Rushing the Doors.
headline.print_headline: Bold Talk on Infrastructure Plan Rings Hollow on Washington’s Subway

docs.abstract: Two of the three jurists on the panel raised doubts that Mick Mulvaney, the White House budget director, could legally run the Consumer Financial Protection Bureau, which is supposed to be independent.

docs.lead_paragraph: The White House budget director, Mick Mulvaney, privately fumed on Thursday that his own staff had been leaking confidential information “to make me look bad,” hours after a federal appeals court questioned whether he could legally run the Consumer Financial Protection Bureau while simultaneously heading the budget office.
